Why is C Called a Middle-Level Language?

Because C combines features of both high-level and low-level languages.

High-Level Features
Functions
Loops
Arrays
Structures

Example:

for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
{
    printf("%d", i);
}
Low-Level Features
Pointers
Direct memory access
Bitwise operations
Hardware programming

Example:

int *ptr = &a;

Since C supports both, it is called a middle-level language.


